# AI Chat Feature — Framework Evaluation Notes

Date: 2026-02-12

## Context

The AI chat feature design (2026-02-10) plans a custom Chat Orchestrator
that manages conversation history, builds LLM prompts, routes between the
LLM and the Monty sandbox, handles tool calls, context management,
cancellation, and lifecycle. This document evaluates whether external
frameworks can replace some or all of that plumbing.

The design targets an OpenAI-compatible HTTP endpoint (not Anthropic-specific),
non-streaming responses for v1, and an in-process Monty sandbox with custom
external functions.

## Frameworks evaluated

### Vercel AI SDK v6 (`ai` + `@ai-sdk/openai-compatible`)

**Version:** 6.0.81 (Feb 2026)

**What it handles:**
- HTTP client with streaming (`streamText()`) and non-streaming (`generateText()`)
- AbortSignal-based cancellation baked into every call
- Tool-call loop via agent class — handles the "LLM emits tool call → execute
  → feed result back → LLM responds again" cycle with configurable step limits
- Multi-provider support — works with any OpenAI-compatible endpoint, which is
  exactly what the design specifies
- Retries built into the provider layer
- Clean TypeScript `Message` types for the conversation array

**What it does NOT handle:**
- Conversation persistence (save/load) — you manage storage
- Session IDs / multi-conversation management — you manage routing
- Context window truncation — no automatic trimming of conversation history
- Token counting — no built-in tokenizer (too large for bundling)

**Electron compatibility:** Excellent. The Core layer (`generateText`,
`streamText`) is plain async functions — no React, no Next.js required.
Works directly in Electron's main process.

**Maturity:** High. 17k+ GitHub stars, backed by Vercel, multiple releases
per week. v6 is stable with documented migration path from v5.

### Anthropic SDK (`@anthropic-ai/sdk`)

**Version:** 0.74.0 (Feb 2026)

Raw API wrapper for Anthropic's API. Handles streaming, cancellation
(`stream.controller.abort()`), tool calling, and retries. Does NOT handle
conversation management, context trimming, session IDs, or persistence.
Anthropic-only by design.

Not a good fit because the design targets OpenAI-compatible endpoints
(Ollama, vLLM, lab servers, cloud APIs), not Anthropic-specific.

**Side note — Claude Agent SDK** (`@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk` v0.2.39):
Has session management (session IDs, resume, fork), lifecycle hooks, and
automatic context compaction. But it's designed for autonomous agents
(Claude Code-style), not a chat feature. Heavyweight and opinionated.
Overkill for this use case.

### LangChain.js (`langchain` / `@langchain/core` / LangGraph)

**Versions:** `langchain` 1.2.21, `@langchain/core` 1.1.22 (Feb 2026)

**What it handles:**
- Conversation memory — multiple strategies:
  - `ConversationBufferMemory` (full history)
  - `ConversationBufferWindowMemory` (last K messages)
  - `ConversationSummaryMemory` (LLM-generated running summary)
- LangGraph adds checkpointed memory with thread IDs — resume by thread ID
- Streaming via LCEL `.stream()` method
- Tool calling via agent abstraction (Monty sandbox → `DynamicStructuredTool`)
- Multi-provider support

**What it does NOT handle well:**
- **Cancellation** — AbortSignal support exists but multiple open GitHub
  issues report buggy behavior in LangGraph.js as of early 2026
- **Simplicity** — large abstraction surface (chains, runnables, LCEL,
  agents, memory classes, checkpointers, graphs) for what is fundamentally
  a simple orchestrator loop
- **Lightweight operation** — heavy dependency tree, assumes server-side
  deployment model

**Electron compatibility:** Works in Node.js but awkward. Large dependency
tree, many features assume server environment.

**Maturity:** Actively maintained (daily releases), large community. But
the JS version is less mature than Python, and the API surface has had
multiple breaking changes (v0.1 → v0.2 → v1.x).

### Mastra (`@mastra/core`)

**Version:** 1.2.0 (Feb 2026)

**What it handles:**
- "Observational Memory" — compresses conversations 5-40x by extracting
  structured observations, supports automatic reflection (summary of
  summaries)
- Thread-scoped and resource-scoped memory
- Streaming (built on Vercel AI SDK primitives)
- Session/thread management built in
- Tool calling with dependency injection
- Multi-provider (via Vercel AI SDK provider layer)
- Has an official Electron integration guide

**What it does NOT handle:**
- **In-process operation** — the Electron guide runs Mastra as a separate
  local HTTP server alongside the Electron app. This is a sidecar
  architecture, not in-process. Adds a second process, IPC over HTTP,
  and an extra port to bind.
- **Simplicity** — full framework with agents, workflows, human-in-the-loop,
  MCP, skills. A lot of machinery for a chat feature.

**Maturity:** v1.0 released January 2026. YC-backed, from the Gatsby team.
One month old. Growing quickly but expect some churn.

### TanStack AI (`@tanstack/ai`)

**Released:** January 2026

Framework-agnostic core with streaming, tool calling, and multi-provider
adapters. Does NOT handle conversation persistence, memory, or session
management. Too new for production use (released weeks ago). Strong
pedigree (TanStack team) but insufficient track record.

### Pi Agent Core (`@mariozechner/pi-agent-core`)

**Version:** 0.52.10 (Feb 2026)
**Repository:** https://github.com/badlogic/pi-mono (monorepo)
**Author:** Mario Zechner (known for libGDX)
**License:** MIT

Stateful AI agent runtime from the Pi monorepo. Pi's flagship product
is a coding agent CLI (`@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent`, marketed at
`shittycodingagent.ai`). The agent package is the reusable core that
the coding agent, a Slack bot, and a web UI are built upon.

**Architecture:** Tiny and focused — 5 source files, ~800 lines of
TypeScript total:

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `types.ts` | All type definitions (AgentMessage, AgentEvent, AgentTool, AgentState) |
| `agent-loop.ts` | Core agentic loop as async generators (`agentLoop`, `agentLoopContinue`) |
| `agent.ts` | Stateful `Agent` class wrapping the loop |
| `proxy.ts` | Proxy streaming for browser-to-server setups |
| `index.ts` | Barrel re-export |

**What it handles:**
- Stateful `Agent` class wrapping model, system prompt, messages, tools,
  thinking level, and streaming state into a single `AgentState` object
- Tool-call loop via async generator — sequential execution (not parallel),
  with TypeBox schemas (`@sinclair/typebox`) for parameter validation
- Fine-grained event streaming: `agent_start`, `turn_start`,
  `message_start`, `message_update`, `message_end`,
  `tool_execution_start`, `tool_execution_update`,
  `tool_execution_end`, `turn_end`, `agent_end`
- Steering and follow-up queues — unique feature allowing users to
  interrupt the agent mid-tool-execution or queue follow-up prompts.
  Supports "one-at-a-time" and "all" modes. After each tool execution,
  the system checks for steering messages; if a user interrupts,
  remaining tool calls are skipped with error results
- Two-phase context transformation pipeline:
  1. `transformContext(messages, signal)` — operates on `AgentMessage[]`
     before every LLM call. Use for token-based pruning, context window
     management, injecting external context
  2. `convertToLlm(messages)` — converts `AgentMessage[]` to LLM-compatible
     `Message[]`. Custom message types are filtered out or transformed here
- Custom message types via TypeScript declaration merging — apps can
  extend `AgentMessage` with custom roles (notifications, artifacts, etc.)
- AbortSignal-based cancellation via `agent.abort()` + `waitForIdle()`
- Dynamic API key resolution via `getApiKey` callback (for expiring
  OAuth tokens, e.g. GitHub Copilot)
- Configurable thinking/reasoning levels: "off", "minimal", "low",
  "medium", "high", "xhigh" with custom token budgets
- Low-level API: `agentLoop()` and `agentLoopContinue()` exported as
  standalone async generator functions for users who don't want the
  `Agent` class

**Tool system details:**
- Tools defined via `AgentTool` interface extending base `Tool` from `pi-ai`
- TypeBox schemas provide both runtime validation and compile-time type
  inference
- Tools can stream partial results via `onUpdate()` callback (emitted
  as `tool_execution_update` events)
- Error convention: tools throw on failure, caught and forwarded to the
  LLM as `isError: true` tool results
- Tool results support text and image content blocks plus arbitrary
  `details` for UI display

**Provider support (via `@mariozechner/pi-ai`):** 20+ providers through
9 registered API backends:

| API Backend | Providers |
|-------------|-----------|
| `anthropic-messages` | Anthropic, Kimi for Coding |
| `openai-completions` | OpenAI, Groq, Cerebras, xAI, OpenRouter, Vercel AI Gateway, Mistral, MiniMax, Huggingface, any OpenAI-compatible (Ollama, vLLM, LM Studio) |
| `openai-responses` | OpenAI (Responses API) |
| `azure-openai-responses` | Azure OpenAI |
| `openai-codex-responses` | OpenAI Codex (ChatGPT Plus/Pro) |
| `google-generative-ai` | Google (Gemini) |
| `google-gemini-cli` | Google Gemini CLI (OAuth) |
| `google-vertex` | Google Vertex AI |
| `bedrock-converse-stream` | Amazon Bedrock |

Additionally supports OAuth flows for GitHub Copilot, Google Antigravity,
OpenAI Codex, and Google Gemini CLI. Only includes models that support
tool calling (required for agentic workflows).

**What it does NOT handle:**
- Conversation persistence (save/load) — state is in-memory
- Session/thread IDs — single agent instance = single conversation
- Output size gating
- Context window truncation (but `transformContext` gives you the hook
  to implement it)

**Electron compatibility:** The agent package itself is plain TypeScript
with no server or React dependencies — works in Electron's main process.
However, the `pi-ai` dependency pulls in every provider SDK (see
dependencies below), which is heavy for a desktop app.

**Dependencies:**
