### Was the recommendation correct?

**Yes, strongly.** The "build the rest yourself" recommendation
underestimated how little even the transport layer needed a framework.
The custom `fetchChatCompletion()` is simpler, more debuggable, and more
maintainable than any SDK wrapper would have been. The total AI chat
implementation is ~11,600 lines with zero third-party AI dependencies —
compared to the thousands of lines of transitive dependencies that even
Vercel AI SDK would have introduced.

The specific patterns worth stealing (two-phase context pipeline, event
taxonomy) were adopted successfully as lightweight architectural
decisions rather than framework dependencies. The brainstorming doc's
conclusion — "this is a type definition, not a framework dependency" —
proved exactly right.

The one thing the brainstorming doc got wrong was recommending Vercel AI
SDK for transport. The transport layer turned out to be the easiest part
to build yourself — an HTTP POST with retry logic is less code than
learning and configuring a third-party SDK that abstracts the same
thing.
